# Recherches sur les stress

Shi et al. (2007) - Recherche interface multimodale

Galvanic Skin Response readings significantly increase when task cognitive load level increases. Moreover, users. GSR readings are found to be lower when using a multimodal interface, instead of a unimodal interface. Cross-examination of GSR data with multimodal data annotation showed promising results in explaining the peaks in the GSR data, which are found to correlate with sub-task user events. This interesting result verifies that GSR can be used to serve as an objective indicator of user cognitive load level in real time, with a very fine granularity.

Luft et al. (2009) - Recherche sur athlètes, sport et tâches cognitives

We conclude that HRV is related to cognitive demand and that the correlation between HRV and cognitive performance seems to be stronger after physical exercise

Healey & Picard (2005) - Recherche sur test conduite

The results show that for most drivers studied, skin conductivity and heart rate metrics are most closely correlated with driver stress level. These findings indicate that physiological signals can provide a metric of driver stress in future cars capable of physiological monitoring

Revue PMC (2025)

Electrodermal activity (EDA) is a powerful anchor for assessing human sympathetic nervous system (SNS) arousal
Modeling arousal requires capturing both SNS and PNS responses. In the context of SNS arousal, modeling is any computational/mathematical framework that maps signals to an inferred arousal state. Although EDA provides a direct measure of sympathetic arousal (sweat gland activity governed by the SNS), heart rate variability (HRV) provides a view primarily into the parasympathetic nervous system. Combining sensors that capture both systems allows for a broader overview of the state of an individual and a more complete reconstruction of the autonomic state that either signal can produce in isolation.

# Recherches sur la concentration / le flow

Rácz et al. (2025)

On the basis of motion tracking, subjects were the least physically active in flow, signifying a focused state, and the most active in boredom

Définition du flow

Les 3 préconditions — ce que tu dois créer dans ton protocole
1. Challenge-Skill Balance
La tâche doit être ni trop facile (→ ennui) ni trop difficile (→ stress). C'est la précondition la plus documentée. C'est le paramètre principal à faire varier dans ton expérience pour induire ou casser la concentration.
2. Clear Goals — Objectifs clairs
Le sujet sait exactement ce qu'il doit faire à chaque instant. Sans clarté, l'attention se fragmente.
3. Unambiguous Feedback — Retour immédiat
Le sujet sait en temps réel s'il réussit ou échoue. Le feedback maintient l'engagement attentionnel.

Caractéristiques du flow 
4. Concentration totale sur la tâche
EDA (SCL stable et modéré), accéléromètre (immobilité)
5. Fusion action-conscience — les actions deviennent automatiques, plus de réflexion consciente
EMG (tonus de base bas et stable, mouvements fluides)
6. Sentiment de contrôle — pas d'anxiété sur l'issue
HRV (modérée et stable, pas effondrée comme sous stress)
7. Perte de conscience de soi — le sujet "oublie" son corps
EMG (tension musculaire parasite réduite)
8. Distorsion du temps — le temps semble passer plus vite
(mesure subjective uniquement, questionnaire post-session)
9. Expérience autotélique — la tâche est intrinsèquement satisfaisante
(mesure subjective uniquement)